# Part 1: The Case That the Run Was Historic

The 2025–26 Knicks went << f("raw.wins") >>-<< f("raw.losses") >> with a << f("raw.margin") >> average margin.
The affirmative case that this was a historically dominant run rests on a handful of measurable claims, each ranked against the << f("raw.n_champions") >> NBA champions since 1983–84.
Each section below states a claim, the test that checked it, what the data showed, and why the result holds up.

## The Raw Run Is the Best on Record

**The claim.** The Knicks' raw playoff dominance ranks at or near the top of every champion since 1983–84.

**The test.** Rank their << f("raw.wins") >>-<< f("raw.losses") >> record and << f("raw.margin") >> average margin against all << f("raw.n_champions") >> champions, and put a range on the margin by re-drawing the << f("ats.n_total") >> games at random thousands of times.

**What the data showed.** The << f("raw.margin") >> average margin is the highest in << f("raw.n_champions") >> years, the << f("raw.margin_pct", "{:.0f}") >>th percentile of the champion set.
The .842 win rate sits at the << f("raw.win_rate_pct", "{:.0f}") >>th percentile, behind a small group led by the 2016–17 Warriors (.941).
Re-drawing the << f("ats.n_total") >> games leaves the average margin anywhere from << f("raw.margin_ci.lo") >> to << f("raw.margin_ci.hi") >> (a 95% range).

**Why it holds.** Even at the unlucky end of that range, the run would still rank above the average champion.
The << f("raw.margin") >> is not the work of one or two blowouts that happened to land in a short sample: it is the best raw margin on record and stays elite across the re-draws.

![Average playoff margin, all 43 champions ranked](../generated/images/knicks_2026_margin_ranking.svg){#fig-margin-ranking width=100%}

## It Survives Adjusting for Opponent Strength

**The claim.** The dominance is not just a soft-schedule artifact.
After crediting opponents for their quality, the Knicks still rank first.

**The test.** Subtract each opponent's rating (weighted by how many games the series ran) from the Knicks' margins, then rank the adjusted figure against all << f("raw.n_champions") >> champions.

**What the data showed.** The opponent-adjusted margin was << f("adj.margin", "{:+.1f}") >> per game, first all-time, ahead of the 2016–17 Warriors (<< f("adj.top2.margin", "{:+.1f}") >>) and the 1986–87 Lakers (<< f("adj.top3.margin", "{:+.1f}") >>).

**Why it holds.** The ranking does not hinge on whether margins or wins drive the rating.
A wins-only system that never sees a single point margin also puts them first (Part 2, "the margins are garbage-time padding"), and the schedule they faced was a median champion's rather than a soft one (Part 2, "the bracket was soft"), so the adjustment is not propping up a weak slate.
The one rating that does move them, off the top to third, is Elo, which weights recent form and rates their late-peaking opponents tougher (Part 2, "the early-round opponents were fading").

![Opponent-adjusted playoff dominance: 2025-26 Knicks rank #1 all-time among 43 champions](../generated/images/knicks_2026_adjusted_margin_ranking.svg){#fig-adjusted-margin-ranking width=100%}

## They Played Far Above Their Own Level

**The claim.** The Knicks did not coast as an already-strong regular-season team.
They elevated more than their own regular season predicted and more than any other team in the 2026 field.

**The test.** Compare their actual playoff margins to what their regular-season rating (<< f("elev.knicks.reg_srs") >>) predicted against those opponents, and compare every 2026 playoff team's jump in rating from the regular season to the playoffs.

**What the data showed.** The Knicks outscored their own forecast by << f("overperf.margin", "{:+.1f}") >> points per game, second among all << f("raw.n_champions") >> champions behind only the 2000–01 Lakers.
Their rating climbed from << f("elev.knicks.reg_srs") >> in the regular season to << f("elev.knicks.po_srs") >> in the playoffs, a << f("elev.knicks.elevation") >> jump: the largest of any team in the 2026 field, and the second-largest by any champion on record.
The team they beat in the Finals, the Spurs, made the second-largest jump in the field (<< f("field.spurs.elevation") >>, from << f("field.spurs.reg_srs") >> to << f("field.spurs.po_srs") >>).
The Finals paired the field's two most-improved teams, which is part of why the series was tight.

**Why it holds.** The elevation shows up in two separate measures, the overperformance against their own forecast and the raw rating jump, both near the top of the field and the historical set.
It also lines up with where the run was actually tested: the Knicks beat the field's best-performing team, fully healthy, in a Finals decided by a << f("finals.raw") >> average margin, not just soft early-round opponents.

![Regular-season to playoff jump in team rating: the Knicks rose more than any 2025-26 playoff team, the Spurs second](../generated/images/knicks_2026_field_elevation.svg){#fig-field-elevation width=100%}

## The Market Saw the Same Two-Sided Run

**The claim.** A benchmark set before the games, the betting market, agreed the Knicks were dominant in the East and tested in the Finals.

**The test.** Compare the betting spread for each game to the actual result, round by round.

**What the data showed.** The Knicks went << f("ats.n_covered") >>-3 against the spread, beating it by << f("ats.avg_margin") >> points a game.
In the three East rounds they covered 14-0, beating the spread by 21 to 26 points a round.
In the Finals the market made them slight underdogs (<< f("ats.finals.spread") >>), and they won by an average of << f("ats.finals.actual") >>, almost exactly the spread.

**Why it holds.** Two cautions keep this from being independent proof.
The << f("ats.n_total") >> games are really four series and move together, so the effective sample is about << f("ats.n_eff") >>; and an against-the-spread margin is mostly the same scoreline read from the bookmaker's side, not a separate measurement of strength.
Even crediting that clustering, the cover record still beats what a coin flip would produce (about a 1-in-25 chance it is a fluke, p ≈ << f("ats.p_clust", "{:.2f}") >>), though with only four series that reads as suggestive, not conclusive.
But the split is the point: the market, pricing in everything known at the time, saw a team that overwhelmed the East and faced a near-coin-flip in the Finals, the same two-sided run the ratings describe.

![Market expectations vs. actual margins: Knicks badly beat the spread against East opponents, Finals were dead-on](../generated/images/knicks_2026_market_vs_actual.svg){#fig-market-vs-actual width=100%}

## The Run Beat Its Own Forecast

**The claim.** From where the Knicks started the playoffs, a << f("raw.wins") >>-<< f("raw.losses") >> title was improbable, so the run measures how far they exceeded expectations rather than a predictable march.

**The test.** A forecaster that knows only each team's regular-season strength and who had home court plays the four best-of-seven rounds tens of thousands of times.

**What the data showed.** The model made the Knicks a Finals underdog (about a << f("winprob.finals.p_series", "{:.0f}") >>% chance to win that series) and gave them about a << f("winprob.p_title", "{:.0f}") >>% chance to win the title at all.
A run as clean as << f("raw.wins") >>-<< f("raw.losses") >> was rarer still: only about << f("winprob.p_le3_given_title", "{:.0f}") >>% of the model's title runs lost three or fewer games, and about << f("winprob.p_title_and_le3", "{:.0f}") >>% of all simulated seasons produced both a title and three or fewer losses.

**Why it holds.** The forecast is built only from regular-season strength, so it captures what was knowable before a single playoff game.
The gap between a roughly << f("winprob.p_title", "{:.0f}") >>% title chance and the actual << f("raw.wins") >>-<< f("raw.losses") >> title is the same overperformance measured above, told in wins and losses instead of point margins.

![How rare a 16-3 run was: from the Knicks' regular season the model gave them a 15% title shot, and a run this clean about 1%](../generated/images/knicks_2026_title_run_rarity.svg){#fig-title-run-rarity width=100%}

